## Wazuh OS_Regex Rules (CRITICAL — different from PCRE)

### Character Classes
  - \\d  = digits 0-9
  - \\w  = A-Z, a-z, 0-9, '-', '@', '_'
  - \\s  = space only (ASCII 32, NOT tabs/newlines)
  - \\p  = punctuation: ()*+,-.:;<=>?[]!"'#$%&|{}
  - \\.  = ANY character (opposite of PCRE!)
  - \\S  = anything not space
  - \\W  = anything not \\w
  - \\D  = anything not \\d
  - \\t  = tab

### Quantifiers (ONLY work on backslash expressions, NOT bare chars)
  - \\d+  = one or more digits  ✓
  - \\w+  = one or more word chars  ✓
  - \\.+  = one or more of any char  ✓
  - a+   = INVALID — bare char quantifier ✗
  - 0+   = INVALID — bare char quantifier ✗

### Anchors
  - ^  = start of text
  - $  = end of text

### Alternation
  - (foo|bar) = NOT supported  ✗
  - Use: ^foo |^bar  (without parens)  ✓

### Gotchas
  - . matches a literal dot (not any char). Use \\. for any char.
  - \\s matches only ASCII space (NOT \\t, \\n).
  - * and + only apply to \\d, \\w, \\s, \\p, \\., \\S, \\W, \\D.

## Sregex (OS_Match)
  - ^ = start, $ = end, | = OR, ! = negation
  - Used in <match> tags for simple substring matching

## Decoder XML Structure Rules
1. Parent decoder with <prematch> or <program_name> for scoping
2. Child decoders with <parent>, <regex>, <order>
3. Use <regex offset="after_parent"> to match after parent consumed text
4. Use <regex offset="after_prematch"> to match after prematch consumed text
5. Use <regex offset="after_regex"> to chain multiple regex matches
6. <order> is comma-separated: <order>srcip,srcport,id</order>
7. Same decoder name can be reused multiple times for different patterns
8. <use_own_name>true</use_own_name> keeps decoder name in alerts
9. <type> can be: web-log, firewall, ossec, windows
10. <program_name> matches process name: ^sshd, ^apache2|^httpd, ^sudo
11. <fts> enables full-text search: <fts>name, user, location</fts>
12. <plugin_decoder>JSON_Decoder</plugin_decoder> for JSON parsing

## Rule XML Structure Rules
1. <decoded_as> points to parent decoder name
2. <if_sid> references parent rule ID for chaining
3. <match> uses sregex (simple substring, | for OR, ! for NOT)
4. <regex> uses OS_Regex in rules too
5. Use static field tags: <srcip>, <dstip>, <srcport>, <dstport>, <protocol>, <action>, <id>, <url>, <status>, <data>, <extra_data>, <system_name>, <user>, <hostname>, <program_name>
6. Use <field name="FIELD">VALUE</field> ONLY for custom fields not in static list
7. Multiple <match> or <field> tags are ANDed

## Output Format
Wrap decoder XML in ```xml ... ``` and rule XML in a separate ```xml ... ``` block.

